on nitrosamines: 

Worth noting - nitrates / nitrites are not toxic to human beings. It's when they form into nitrosamines (in the case of bacon, when heat is added) they become carcinogenic. But you can greatly minimize the formation of nitrosamines, if not prevent their formation entirely, in a few ways: 
1) cook your bacon below 300F. I bake mine at 275F for 20 minutes... it actually tastes better, in my opinion... it has the characteristic bacon taste but it's not dried out. You'll get minimal nitrosamine formation at these temps. Even lower temps (266F) can almost completely prevent their formation, though I have not experimented with cooking at temperatures that low yet, but will soon - 275F is shockingly fine though. 
2) include something with ascorbic acid (Vitamin C) and/or tocopherals (Vitamin E) when curing the bacon, they inhibit nitrosamine formation
3) use celery extract - while it contains nitrates, it also contains chemicals that inhibit nitrosamine formation 
4) add sodium ascorbate or sodium erythorbate during the curing process as well - these inhibit nitrosamine formation, and are now commonly added to processed meats in the US for this reason
